Certainly, here's a simple C++ program that demonstrates the use of input and output, as well as a basic function. This program will ask the user for their name and greet them.

```cpp
#include <iostream> // For input/output stream
#include <string>   // For std::string

// Function to greet the user
void greet(const std::string& name) {
    std::cout << "Hello, " << name << "! Welcome to C++ programming!" << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    std::string userName;

    // Get user's name
    std::cout << "Please enter your name: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, userName); // Use std::getline to handle spaces in the name

    // Greet the user
    greet(userName);

    return 0; // Indicate successful execution of the program
}
```

To compile and run this program, you would typically use a command like `g++` to compile it, and then execute the resulting binary:

```bash
g++ -o greet_program greet.cpp
./greet_program
```

Replace `greet.cpp` with the name of your source file if you save the code under a different name. After running the program, it will wait for you to input your name, after which it will greet you.

Certainly, here's a simple Java program that prints "Hello, World!" to the console:

```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Output the string "Hello, World!" to the console
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

To run this program, you would save it to a file named `HelloWorld.java`, then compile it with the `javac` command, and finally run it with the `java` command:

```bash
javac HelloWorld.java
java HelloWorld
```

After running the program, you should see `Hello, World!` printed to the console.
